    {
      "id": "85871486452fc0d5a43c21c6128624596a6809fb",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 464,
        "name": "Elena",
        "email": "elena.gryaznova@hpe.com",
        "username": "elena"
      },
      "date": "2019-04-18 15:34:15.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1\n\n(1 comment)",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "2bfa2a7f7589c3cdc41dd2085d085cac24a1ed1e",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2019-04-18 16:16:46.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\n> this causes the tests always run with particular index.\n > I.e. for example sanity test_120 tests \"\"Early Lock Cancel: \" never\n > run with mdt_index other than equal to 0.\n > Instead of reverting the t-f improvement which allows to enlarge\n > striped directories Lustre Feature testing it looks more reasonable\n > to investigate the mentioned tests failures and fix the tests or Lustre.\n\nElena, you are correct that this patch removes the MDT randomization\nadded in your patch, however it leaves the (AFAIK) original functionality \nthat you cared about, which is testing compatibility with older releases.\n\nThe other alternative is to revert the whole patch, because this change\nis causing a large number of test failures, which is causing many other\npatches to fail testing, and hurting patch landing as a result.  Since the\ntesting behavior is now random, it will take much longer to verify if a \"fix\"\nis actually fixing a test failure or just randomly passing.\n\nMy preference is to land this patch to keep the other functionality intact,\nbut if you want to revert the whole patch until you fix it that is also possible.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "7fd07817c30217aa03fc1401d22ea0dc162aa985",
